{"title_page": "Alexander Frick", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Alexander Frick\n|image       =\n|office      = [[List of heads of government of Liechtenstein|Prime Minister of Liechtenstein]]\n|deputy      = [[Ferdinand Nigg]]<br/>[[Josef B\u00fcchel]]<ref name=\"officehistory\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.regierung.li/regierungsmitglieder/mitglieder|title=Mitglieder der Regierung des F\u00fcrstentums Liechtenstein 1862-2021|website=www.regierung.li}}</ref>\n|monarch     = [[Franz Joseph II, Prince of Liechtenstein|Franz Joseph II]]\n|term_start  = 3 September 1945\n|term_end    = 16 July 1962\n|predecessor = [[Josef Hoop]]\n|successor   = [[Gerard Batliner]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1910|2|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1991|10|31|1910|2|18|df=y}}\n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Progressive Citizens' Party]]\n}}\nDr. '''Alexander Frick''' (18 February 1910 \u2013 31 October 1991) was a political figure from [[Liechtenstein]].\n\n==Earlier life==\n\nFrom 1929 until 1936 he was a civil servant for the Liechtenstein fiscal administration, becoming director in 1936 and serving until 1945. In 1931 he founded the [[Pfadfinder und Pfadfinderinnen Liechtensteins|Scouts of Liechtenstein]]. From 1935 until 1937 he served as chairman of the National Olympic Committee of Liechtenstein.\n\n==Prime Minister of Liechtenstein==\n\nHe was the [[List of Liechtenstein Heads of Government|Regierungschef]] (head of government) of [[Liechtenstein]] from 3 September 1945 until 16 July 1962, serving as a member of the [[Progressive Citizens' Party]].<ref name=\"officehistory\" />\n\n==Subsequent roles and honours==\n\nIn 1961 he was awarded a doctorate ''honoris causa'' from the [[University of Fribourg]].\n\nFollowing his service as head of the government, he became deputy of the Diet from 1966 until 1974. He served as its [[List of presidents of the Landtag of Liechtenstein|President of the Landtag]] from January 1966 until December 1969.<ref name=\"pr\u00e4sidenten\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327123617/https://www.landtag.li/praesidenten.aspx?nid=4159&groupnr=4159|title=Mitglieder - Pr\u00e4sidenten|date=March 27, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> \n\nIn 1957, Frick was awarded the [[Decoration of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria|Grand Decoration of Honour in Silver with Sash for Services to the Republic of Austria]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.parlament.gv.at/PAKT/VHG/XXIV/AB/AB_10542/imfname_251156.pdf | title = Reply to a parliamentary question | language = German | page=38 |trans-title=| format = pdf | accessdate = 2 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nHis son Hansj\u00f6rg Frick was a member of the government from 2001 until 2005.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Scouting}}\n\n* [[Politics of Liechtenstein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{HDS|21115|Alexander Frick}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070310191508/http://www.time.com/time/archive/printout/0,23657,854470,00.html TIME archive article]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box|\n before = [[Josef Hoop]] |\n title = [[Head of Government of Liechtenstein]]|\n years = 1945-1962 |\n after = [[Gerard Batliner]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LiechtensteinPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frick, Alexander}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heads of government of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Landtag of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Progressive Citizens' Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Decoration with Sash for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n[[Category:Scouting in Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Scouting pioneers]]\n\n\n{{Liechtenstein-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Alexander Frick\n|image       =\n|office      = [[List of heads of government of Liechtenstein|Prime Minister of Liechtenstein]]\n|deputy      = [[Ferdinand Nigg]]<br/>[[Josef B\u00fcchel]]<ref name=\"officehistory\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.regierung.li/regierungsmitglieder/mitglieder|title=Mitglieder der Regierung des F\u00fcrstentums Liechtenstein 1862-2021|website=www.regierung.li}}</ref>\n|monarch     = [[Franz Joseph II, Prince of Liechtenstein|Franz Joseph II]]\n|term_start  = 3 September 1945\n|term_end    = 16 July 1962\n|predecessor = [[Josef Hoop]]\n|successor   = [[Gerard Batliner]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1910|2|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1991|10|31|1910|2|18|df=y}}\n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Progressive Citizens' Party]]\n}}\nDr. '''Alexander Frick''' (18 February 1910 \u2013 31 October 1991) was a political figure from [[Liechtenstein]].\n\n==Earlier life==\n\nFrom 1929 until 1936 he was a civil servant for the Liechtenstein fiscal administration, becoming director in 1936 and serving until 1945. In 1931 he founded the [[Pfadfinder und Pfadfinderinnen Liechtensteins|Scouts of Liechtenstein]]. From 1935 until 1937 he served as chairman of the National Olympic Committee of Liechtenstein.\n\n==Prime Minister of Liechtentein==\n\nHe was the [[List of Liechtenstein Heads of Government|Regierungschef]] (head of government) of [[Liechtenstein]] from 3 September 1945 until 16 July 1962, serving as a member of the [[Progressive Citizens' Party]].<ref name=\"officehistory\" />\n\n==Subsequent roles and honours==\n\nIn 1961 he was awarded a doctorate ''honoris causa'' from the [[University of Fribourg]].\n\nFollowing his service as head of the government, he became deputy of the Diet from 1966 until 1974. He served as its [[List of presidents of the Landtag of Liechtenstein|President of the Landtag]] from January 1966 until December 1969.<ref name=\"pr\u00e4sidenten\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327123617/https://www.landtag.li/praesidenten.aspx?nid=4159&groupnr=4159|title=Mitglieder - Pr\u00e4sidenten|date=March 27, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> \n\nIn 1957, Frick was awarded the [[Decoration of Honour for Services to the Republic of Austria|Grand Decoration of Honour in Silver with Sash for Services to the Republic of Austria]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.parlament.gv.at/PAKT/VHG/XXIV/AB/AB_10542/imfname_251156.pdf | title = Reply to a parliamentary question | language = German | page=38 |trans-title=| format = pdf | accessdate = 2 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nHis son Hansj\u00f6rg Frick was a member of the government from 2001 until 2005.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Scouting}}\n\n* [[Politics of Liechtenstein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{HDS|21115|Alexander Frick}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070310191508/http://www.time.com/time/archive/printout/0,23657,854470,00.html TIME archive article]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box|\n before = [[Josef Hoop]] |\n title = [[Head of Government of Liechtenstein]]|\n years = 1945-1962 |\n after = [[Gerard Batliner]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LiechtensteinPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frick, Alexander}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heads of government of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Landtag of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Progressive Citizens' Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Decoration with Sash for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n[[Category:Scouting in Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Scouting pioneers]]\n\n\n{{Liechtenstein-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Liechtentein->Liechtenstein -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Frick"}
